cations. I might have to refine tests, maybe even write an explanatory test. There's some older ineffective tests that I could delete, but keeping them might still be okay for context.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Examining closure class coverage**\\n\\nI'm considering mapping the closure3 class in a dedicated file since it seems to be a one-to-one match already. Without modifications, it looks like coverage will be marked as unsupported. The challenge is figuring out if using `InvokerHelper.invokeStaticMethod` to call the synthetic `class$` method can help improve coverage. This method can run natively but requires reflection metadata. The `class$` method is package-private, yet Groovy's MetaClass might still be able to invoke it. So I think I should devise a test using dynamic class loading and reflection!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "I investigated the remaining call site for:\n\n`io.restassured.internal.ResponseSpecificationImpl$_HamcrestAssertionClosure_validate_closure3.class$`\n\nThe uncovered `Class#forName(String)` call is inside Groovy’s synthetic `class$(String)` helper method. That helper is not invoked by the closure’s supported execution path:\n\n- constructor calls `$getCallSiteArray`\n- `doCall` reads `errorMessage`\n- static initialization calls `__$swapInit`\n- call-site array creation uses class literals directly, not `class$`\n\nThe existing/added public-API test reaches the validation-error aggregation behavior that creates and executes `validate_closure3`, but it cannot reach the synthetic `class$` method through Rest Assured’s normal public API.\n\nI did not add a direct reflective or Groovy-MOP invocation of `class$`, because that would exercise an internal compiler artifact rather than supported Rest Assured behavior and would violate the “normal public API / no direct reflection” rules. Therefore the remaining call site should stay uncovered unless the harness allows synthetic Groovy `class$` helpers to be excluded or cov